Question 1

This data was collected from www.theramenrater.com. It provides information on different reviews of ramen products, and has variables: Review #, Brand, Variety, Style, Country, Stars, and Top Ten.

(a)

Read in the Ramen data and check it carefully.

ramen_ratings = read_csv("./data/ramen-ratings.csv")

(b)

Rename the first variable to be review_number, and the last variable to be top_ten. Additionally, ensure that the Stars column is saved as a numeric variable, and remove any non-numeric entries.

ramen_ratings = ramen_ratings %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  filter(stars != "Unrated") %>% 
  mutate(stars = as.numeric(stars))

(c)

Filtering just for the the Nissin ramen brand, calculate the average rating for each country of this brand. What country has the highest rating of Nissin ramen? What country has the lowest rating?

nissin_ramen_country = ramen_ratings %>% 
  filter(brand == "Nissin") %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  summarise(stars_mean = mean(stars))

low_to_high <- nissin_ramen_country %>%
  arrange(stars_mean)

high_to_low <- nissin_ramen_country %>%
  arrange(desc(stars_mean))

Answer:

The country with the highest average rating is Brazil and the country with the lowest average rating is the Philippines.

(d)

Create a new variable called popular which returns a 1 for entries that have a rating above or equal to 4.5 stars, and 0 for those that dont.

ramen_ratings = ramen_ratings %>% 
  mutate(popular = if_else(stars >= 4.5, 1, 0))

(e)

Calculate the average stars for popular and not popular bowl ramen. Explain why (or why not) your results are meaningful.

ramen_ratings %>% filter(style == "Bowl") %>% 
  group_by(popular) %>% 
  summarise(mean(stars))
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   popular `mean(stars)`
##     <dbl>         <dbl>
## 1       0          3.28
## 2       1          4.83

Answer:

This result is not meaningful. Summarizing by stars is redundant because the variable popular was created using the variable stars. It would not make sense to test the difference in stars between these two groups because we have defined them based on their star rating.

(a)

Read in NYC Airbnb data AB_NYC_2019.csv, and select only the: host_name, neighbourhood_group, room_type, price, minimum_nights, and number_of_reviews. Note, the neighborhood_group variable refers to borough.

(b)

Create a new variable called minimum_price, which combines the minimum nights and price (per night) to give the minimum amount someone could pay to stay at the Airbnb.

nyc_airbnb_mp = nyc_airbnb %>% 
  mutate(minimum_price = minimum_nights * price)

(c)

Calculate the mean and median minimum_price using summarize. From these results, estimate whether you expect the data to be left or right skewed? Confirm your hypothesis by creating a histogram. Note, to improve the visualization of your histogram, consider removing very high prices.

nyc_airbnb_mp %>% 
  summarize(
    mean_min_price = mean(minimum_price),
    median_mean_price = median(minimum_price)
    )
## # A tibble: 1  2
##   mean_min_price median_mean_price
##            <dbl>             <dbl>
## 1          1284.               300
nyc_airbnb_mp %>% 
  filter(minimum_price < 10000) %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = minimum_price), bins = 100)

Answer:

The fact that the mean is so much larger than the median makes me think that this distribution will be right-skewed. Even after removing very high prices, we can see that the histogram confirms our suspicions: there is a long right tail to the distribution.

Question 3

(a)

You have been given a dataset for a study of a potential depression drug: STUDYDAT12014.csv. It includes treatment and placebo status, dose, age, along with HAM-D and HAM-A scores at baseline (baseline_hamd and baseline_hama) and at the end of the study (outcome_hamd and outcome_hama). Read in this dataset (STUDYDAT12014.csv) and report how many variables and how many observations are in this dataset.

study = read_csv("./data/STUDYDAT12014.csv")

(b)

The investigators are interested in analyzing subjects who are at least 30 years old but less than 40 years old, so create a dataset which contains only observations from people within this age range. Use this dataset for all subsequent analyses.

study_new = study %>% 
  filter(age >= 30 & age < 40)

(c)

The treatment groups are currently labeled pbo and trx, but the researchers would like to have them labeled Placebo and Drug 13XA. Please make these changes to the dataset you created in (b)

study_new = study_new %>% 
  mutate(trx = ifelse(trx == "pbo", "Placebo", "Drug 13XA"))

## Please use the mutate function!

(d)

Create two new variables hamd_diff and hama_diff that are changes between baseline and outcome measurements for HAM-A and HAM-D.

study_new = study_new %>% 
  mutate(hamd_diff = baseline_hamd - outcome_hamd,
         hama_diff = baseline_hama - outcome_hama)

(e)

The investigators are interested in assessing whether there is a difference in (1) mean HAM-A changes between treatment groups and (2) mean HAM-D changes between treatment groups. Use t-tests (unequal variance) to test the difference between treatment groups for both of these outcomes. Be sure to report the test statistic, p-value, and degrees of freedom for each test in your write-up.

#ham-a t-test
hama_test = t.test(hama_diff ~ trx, data = study_new)

#ham-d t-test
hamd_test = t.test(hamd_diff ~ trx, data = study_new)

## With equal variances:

#ham-a t-test
hama_test_e = t.test(hama_diff ~ trx, data = study_new, var.equal = TRUE)

#ham-d t-test
hamd_test_e = t.test(hamd_diff ~ trx, data = study_new, var.equal = TRUE)

Answer:

Unequal variance t-test:

The test for differences in HAM-A changes between treatment groups resulted in a test statistic of 1.0012236 with a df of 38.9376515 and a corresponding p-value of 0.3229005. Therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis and conclude there is not enough evidence of a significant difference in HAM-A change between treatment groups, at a level of significance of 5%.

The test for differences in HAM-D changes between treatment groups resulted in a test statistic of -0.8025073 with a df of 45.1303189 and a corresponding p-value of 0.4264656. Therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis and conclude there is not enough evidence of a significant difference in HAM-D change between treatment groups, at a level of significance of 5%.

Equal variance t-test:

The test for differences in HAM-A changes between treatment groups resulted in a test statistic of 1.0506664 with a df of 67 and a corresponding p-value of 0.2971867. Therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis and conclude there is not enough evidence of a significant difference in HAM-A change between treatment groups, at a level of significance of 5%.

The test for differences in HAM-D changes between treatment groups resulted in a test statistic of -0.7956345 with a df of 67 and a corresponding p-value of 0.4290544. Therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis and conclude there is not enough evidence of a significant difference in HAM-D change between treatment groups, at a level of significance of 5%.

Question 4

(a)

You have been provided with a dataset from a student-run cafe cafedata.xls. This dataset contains data from a cafe, called Executive Express, run by undergraduate business students at a Midwestern public university. It was collected over a ten-week period from January to April 2010. Use what you have learned to read the data in, prepare it for analysis, and then calculate the necessary summary statistics to fill out the paragraph below, replacing the Xs with appropriate results.

cafe = read_excel("./data/cafedata.xls", sheet = 2) %>%
  janitor::clean_names() %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  mutate(profitable = ifelse(sales >= 160, 1, 0), #create variable indicating profitability
         pastries_sold = muffins_sold + cookies_sold) #create variable combining cookie and muffin sales

cafe_sum = cafe %>%
  group_by(profitable) %>% 
  summarise(n = n(),
            mean_wraps = mean(wraps_sold), sd_wraps = sd(wraps_sold),
            mean_pastries = mean(pastries_sold), sd_pastries = sd(pastries_sold),
            mean_coffees = mean(coffees), sd_coffees = sd(coffees))

cafe_profitable = filter(cafe_sum, profitable == 1)
cafe_unprofitable = filter(cafe_sum, profitable == 0)

# Unequal Variance
t_coffee = t.test(coffees ~ profitable, data = cafe)
t_wraps = t.test(wraps_sold ~ profitable, data = cafe)
t_pastries = t.test(pastries_sold ~ profitable, data = cafe)

#Equal Variance
t_coffee_e = t.test(coffees ~ profitable, data = cafe, var.equal = TRUE)
t_wraps_e = t.test(wraps_sold ~ profitable, data = cafe, var.equal = TRUE)
t_pastries_e = t.test(pastries_sold ~ profitable, data = cafe, var.equal = TRUE)

Answer:

Students called a day a profitable day, when they had at least $160 in sales. There were 18 profitable days and 29 unprofitable days.

On profitable days, the mean number of wraps sold was 16.1111111 with a standard deviation of 6.8245999. On unprofitable days, the mean number of wraps sold was 11.3103448 with a standard deviation of 4.3760994.

On profitable days, on average they sold 13.7777778 muffins and cookies combined, with a standard deviation of 7.352915. On unprofitable days, on average they sold 10.3103448 muffins and cookies combined, with a standard deviation of 6.5416438.

The mean number of coffees sold on profitable days was 25.6111111 with a standard deviation of 8.4445519 and the mean number of coffees sold on unprofitable days was 18.9655172 with a standard deviation of 11.8697778.

Unequal Variances:

When comparing profitable to nonprofitable days, there was a significant difference in coffee sold (p-value = 0.0303483, t=-2.2376848, df=44.0449661), and in wraps sold (p-value = 0.0131412, t=-2.6638622, df=25.7654393). However, the sales of muffins and cookies did not significantly differ between profitable and nonprofitable days (p-value = 0.1108585, t=-1.6383443, df=32.9745634), at a level of significance of 5%.

Equal Variances:

When comparing profitable to nonprofitable days, there was a significant difference in coffee sold (p-value = 0.044339, t=-2.0687955, df=45), and in wraps sold (p-value = 0.0050946, t=-2.9451445, df=45). However, the sales of muffins and cookies did not significantly differ between profitable and nonprofitable days (p-value = 0.0989822, t=-1.6846419, df=45), at a level of significance of 5%.
